When death rates are greater than birth rates and if the population is below its positive equilibrium (“carrying capacity”), then the population shrinks to 0. When death rates are greater than birth rates and if the population is above its positive equilibrium, then the population grows (strange—right?) then becomes negative (this is getting weirder), and lastly grows again until it asymptotes at 0.

4.3

Recall the population model of the Ricker equation from chapter 1 \[N_{t+1} = rN_t\exp(1 - bN_t)\]. Let \(r = 2.5\) and \(b = 2.5\) and project the population 45 times units, beginning with an initial population size of 0.01. What is the pattern of the time series (don’t forget this is a discrete-time equation)?

Ricker <- function(t, N, parms) {
  with(as.list(c(N, parms)), {
  Nt <- r*N*exp(1 - b*N)
  return(list(Nt))
  })
}

N0_4.3_a <- 0.01
parameters_a <- c(r = 2.5, b = 2.5)
times_4.3_a <- 0:45
out_4.3_a <- ode(y = N0_4.3_a, times = times_4.3_a, func = Ricker, parms = parameters_a, method = "iteration")
plot(x = out_4.3_a[,1], y = out_4.3_a[,2], las = 1, pch = 16, cex = 1.25, xlab = "Time steps", ylab = "Density (N)")
lines(x = out_4.3_a[,1], y = out_4.3_a[,2])

N0_4.3_b <- 3.5
parameters_b <- c(r = 4, b = 0.7)
times_4.3_b <- 0:45
out_4.3_b <- ode(y = N0_4.3_b, times = times_4.3_b, func = Ricker, parms = parameters_b, method = "iteration")
plot(x = out_4.3_b[,1], y = out_4.3_b[,2], las = 1, pch = 16, cex = 1.25, xlab = "Time steps", ylab = "Density (N)")
lines(x = out_4.3_b[,1], y = out_4.3_b[,2])

The pattern of the time series for the first part (“(a)”) is that the popluation grows asymptotically towards around a density of 3. In (b), the population starts off large, then shrinks really small, then grows again until it reaches a positive equilibrium value.

4.9

Assume that a population is growing according to the logistic equation. To make things simple, presume that the value of both \(r\) and \(K\) is 1.0 (i.e., we represent the population as varying between 0 and 1). The equilibrium value will be \[0 = N - N^2\], which is a quadratic equation and has two roots, which are, by inspection, 0 and 1. Now suppose that a manager decides to impose a fixed harvesting rate on the popluation such that a constant number of individuals will be removed each year. A sensible model for this situation might be \[\frac{dN}{dt} = N(1 - N) - N_F\], where \(N_F\) is the fixed number (actually the proportion) of individuals removed. Plot the derivative versus \(N\) for the following values of \(N_F\): 0, 0.125, 0.25, and 0.5. Also, directly solve for the roots (using the quadrative formula; remember, \(N_F\) is a constant). What do you conclude?

densities_4.9 <- seq(0, 1.6, by = 0.01)

NFa <- 0
NFb <- 0.125
NFc <- 0.25
NFd <- 0.5

derv_4.9a <- densities_4.9*(1 - densities_4.9) - NFa
derv_4.9b <- densities_4.9*(1 - densities_4.9) - NFb
derv_4.9c <- densities_4.9*(1 - densities_4.9) - NFc
derv_4.9d <- densities_4.9*(1 - densities_4.9) - NFd
plot(x = densities_4.7, y = derv_4.9a, ylim = c(-1.5, 0.6), type = "l", lwd = 2, xlab = "Density (N)", ylab = "Derivative (dN/dt)", las = 1)
lines(x = densities_4.7, y = derv_4.9b, lwd = 2, col = "red")
lines(x = densities_4.7, y = derv_4.9c, lwd = 2, col = "blue")
lines(x = densities_4.7, y = derv_4.9d, lwd = 2, col = "orange")
segments(x0 = -1, x1 = 3, y0 = 0, y1 = 0, col = "#00000055", lty = "33")

The roots when \(N_F = 0\) is just like the logistic when \(r\) and \(K\) are 1: \(N^* = 0\) and \(N^* = 1\). When \(N_F = 0.125\), there are two roots: \(N^* = \frac{5-\sqrt{15}}{10}\) and \(N^* = \frac{5+\sqrt{15}}{10}\). When \(N_F = 0.25\), there is a single root: \(N^* = 0.5\). When \(N_F = 0.5\) there are no roots. I conclude that proportional harvesting can constantly decrease the rate of change of a population and can change the number of equilibria. Given the parameters in this model, harvesting rates \(0.25 >N_F > 0\) of the population size resuled in a lower positive equilibrium and could result in extinction \((N^* = 0)\) if the popluation wasn’t large enough. Above 1/4 of the population and the population always decreased to extinction.

4.10

In chapter 1 (exercise 1.17) you used the logistic map to project the population 50 times with values of \(\lambda = 1.5\text{, }2.0\text{, }3.0\text{, and }3.5\). Do the same for \(\lambda = 3.4\text{, } 3.5\text{, } 3.56\text{, } 3.565\text{, and } 3.567\), starting with 0.8 individuals and projecting 100 time steps (include plots). Note that at the end of the run the numbers tend to repeat themselves in a regular sequence, For example, for \(\lambda = 3.4\) the numbers go from 0.452 to 0.842 and then back again to 0.452, which is to say that there is a two-point cycle. How many points are in the cycles at the ends of the runs of the other values of \(\lambda\)? Plot the last 20 values of each trajectory (vertical axis) against the value of \(\lambda\) on the same graph.

La <- 3.4
Lb <- 3.5
Lc <- 3.56
Ld <- 3.565
Le <- 3.567
N0_4.10 <- 0.8
times_4.10 <- 0:100

log.map <- function(t, N, parms) {
  with(as.list(c(N, parms)), {
  Nt1 <- parms*N*(1 - N)
  return(list(Nt1))
})
}

out_4.10a <- ode(y = N0_4.10, func = log.map, times = times_4.10, parms = La, method = "iteration")
out_4.10b <- ode(y = N0_4.10, func = log.map, times = times_4.10, parms = Lb, method = "iteration")
out_4.10c <- ode(y = N0_4.10, func = log.map, times = times_4.10, parms = Lc, method = "iteration")
out_4.10d <- ode(y = N0_4.10, func = log.map, times = times_4.10, parms = Ld, method = "iteration")
out_4.10e <- ode(y = N0_4.10, func = log.map, times = times_4.10, parms = Le, method = "iteration")

par(mfrow = c(2, 3), mar = c(4, 4, 1, 1))
plot(x = out_4.10a[,1], y = out_4.10a[,2], las = 1, xlab = "Time step", ylab = "Density", lwd = 2, type = "l", ylim = c(0, 1))
plot(x = out_4.10b[,1], y = out_4.10b[,2], las = 1, xlab = "Time step", ylab = "Density", lwd = 2, type = "l", ylim = c(0, 1))
plot(x = out_4.10c[,1], y = out_4.10c[,2], las = 1, xlab = "Time step", ylab = "Density", lwd = 2, type = "l", ylim = c(0, 1))
plot(x = out_4.10d[,1], y = out_4.10d[,2], las = 1, xlab = "Time step", ylab = "Density", lwd = 2, type = "l", ylim = c(0, 1))
plot(x = out_4.10e[,1], y = out_4.10e[,2], las = 1, xlab = "Time step", ylab = "Density", lwd = 2, type = "l", ylim = c(0, 1))

plot(x = rep(x = 3.4, times = 20), y = out_4.10a[82:101,2], pch = 16, las = 1, xlab = bquote(lambda), ylab = "Density (N)", ylim = c(0, 1))

4.Extra

Now we wish to look to see how the cycling (or lack thereof) occurs over a greater range of \(\lambda\). Create a sequence of \(\lambda\)s from 2.5 to 4 by one one-thousandth. Then, create a loop that numerically solves the logistic map for each value of \(\lambda\) and ads points to a preexisting graph (change your pointsize using cex = 0.25 [the default is 1.0] within points() and change your point types to solid using pch = 16). This will probably be your first bifurction diagram—revel in it after you’re finished.

lambdas <- seq(from = 2.5, to = 4, by = 0.001)
n.lambdas <- length(lambdas)
N0_4Ex <- N0_4.10
times_4Ex <- times_4.10

log.map <- function(t, N, parms) {
  with(as.list(c(N, parms)), {
  Nt1 <- parms*N*(1 - N)
  return(list(Nt1))
})
}


plot(x = NA, type = "n", pch = 16, las = 1, xlab = bquote(lambda), ylab = "Density (N)", ylim = c(0, 1), xlim = c(2.5, 4))

for(i in 1:n.lambdas) {
out.loop <- ode(y = N0_4Ex, func = log.map, times = times_4Ex, parms = lambdas[i], method = "iteration")
points(x = rep(x = lambdas[i], times = 20), y = out.loop[82:101,2], pch = 16, cex = 0.25, col = "black")
}
